4 SYNOPSIS:
5 This bill would require a retail establishment
6 that has an employee toilet facility to allow customers
7 with medical conditions that require immediate access
8 to a toilet facility to use an employee toilet facility
9 under certain conditions.
10 This bill would require that a customer
11 requesting access to an employee toilet facility
12 provide evidence of his or her medical condition to the
13 retail establishment.
14 This bill would provide that a retail
15 establishment providing access to an employee toilet
16 facility does not owe a customer a greater degree of
17 care than is owed to a licensee on the premises.
18 This bill would not require a retail
19 establishment to make any physical changes to an
20 employee toilet facility.
21 This bill would establish that a refusal to
22 comply with this act is a misdemeanor offense
23 punishable by a fine.
24
25
26 A BILL
27 TO BE ENTITLED
28 AN ACT
Page 1

AN ACT
HB478 INTRODUCED
29
30 Relating to public restrooms; to create the Restroom
31 Access Act; to require retail establishments to provide
32 restroom access to customers with eligible medical conditions;
33 to provide that a retail establishment does not owe a greater
34 duty of care to a customer accessing employee toilet
35 facilities than is owed to a licensee on the premises; and to
36 provide that a violation of this act is a misdemeanor
37 punishable by fine.
38 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF ALABAMA:
39 Section 1. (a) This section shall be known as and may
40 be cited as the "Restroom Access Act."
41 (b) For the purposes of this section, the following
42 terms have the following meanings:
43 (1) CUSTOMER. An individual who is lawfully on the
44 premises of a retail establishment.
45 (2) ELIGIBLE MEDICAL CONDITION. Crohn's disease,
46 ulcerative colitis, irritable bowel syndrome, or any other
47 permanent or temporary medical condition that requires
48 immediate access to a toilet facility.
49 (3) RETAIL ESTABLISHMENT. A place of business open to
50 the general public for the sale of goods or services.
51 (c) A retail establishment that has a toilet facility
52 for its employees shall allow a customer to use that facility
53 during normal business hours if all of the following
54 conditions are met:
55 (1) The retail establishment does not have a public
56 restroom that is immediately accessible to the customer.
Page 2

restroom that is immediately accessible to the customer.
HB478 INTRODUCED
57 (2) The employee toilet facility is not located in an
58 area where providing access would create an obvious health or
59 safety risk to the customer or an obvious security risk to the
60 retail establishment.
61 (3) The customer requesting the use of the employee
62 toilet facility suffers from an eligible medical condition,
63 and the customer provides the retail establishment with
64 evidence of the customer's eligible medical condition,
65 including:
66 a. A copy of a statement signed by a physician,
67 registered nurse, physician assistant, or a person acting
68 under the delegation and supervision of a licensed physician,
69 that indicates the customer suffers from an eligible medical
70 condition or uses an ostomy device; or
71 b. An identification card issued by the Crohn's &
72 Colitis Foundation of America that indicates the customer
73 suffers from an eligible medical condition or uses an ostomy
74 device.
75 (4) Three or more employees of the retail establishment
76 are working and physically present on the premises of the
77 retail establishment at the time the customer requests to use
78 the employee toilet facility.
79 (d) In providing access to an employee toilet facility
80 under this section, the retail establishment or employee does
81 not owe the customer to whom access is provided a greater
82 degree of care than is owed to a licensee on the premises.
83 (e) A retail establishment is not required to make any
84 physical changes to an employee toilet facility under this
Page 3

physical changes to an employee toilet facility under this
HB478 INTRODUCED
85 section.
86 (f) An employee of a retail establishment who refuses
87 to provide a customer with access to an employee toilet
88 facility as required by this section commits a misdemeanor
89 punishable by a fine of not more than one hundred dollars
90 ($100).
91 Section 2. This act shall become effective on October
92 1, 2026.
